Distribution Center PCD – Traffic Signal Warrant Study
Mason Avenue Extension and Dunn Avenue
Lassiter Transportation Group, Inc. (LTG) was retained by Consolidated-Tomoka Land Company to prepare this
traffic signal warrant study (TSWS) at the intersections of Dunn Avenue and the planned extension of Mason
Avenue. This TSWS will include the impacts of a proposed Distribution Center PCD, consisting of 631,000
square feet (sq. ft.) of high cube refrigerated and frozen distribution space. The Distribution Center is scheduled
for build-out in year 2015. Access to the development will be provided from Mason Avenue and Dunn Avenue.
Also, traffic generation from future development along the portion of Mason Avenue between Williamson
Boulevard and Dunn Avenue within the Gateway Business Center is included in the analysis. Figure 1 shows the
location of the proposed project and Figure 2 shows the other potential development sites within the Gateway
Business Center, as well as the intersection to be evaluated against traffic signal warrant thresholds.
Dunn Avenue is a two-lane, undivided facility, posted for travel at 45 miles-per-hour (mph) in the vicinity of the
Mason Avenue Extension which will be constructed in conjunction with the Distribution Center PCD facilities. The
Mason Avenue Extension will be constructed as a two-lane facility. Traffic volume counts were conducted during
a 24-hour period on Dunn Avenue in the vicinity of the proposed Mason Avenue Extension. The raw traffic count
data is included in Exhibit A.
The a.m. and p.m. peak-hour trip generation for the build-out of the development was determined using the traffic
counts provided by the client in Table 1 for an existing 600,000 square foot facility (see Exhibit B for client-
supplied data for a similar site). Information regarding trip generation as determined by the Institute of
Edition of the Trip Generation Manual is presented in Table 2 for comparison.
As noted, the trip generation provided by the client is higher than the trip generation estimates based on ITE.
Accordingly, the client-supplied data will be used in the analysis for conservative impact determination. The peak-
hour counts and daily count were increased by 5.25 percent since the proposed facility is slightly larger (600,000

The external project trip distribution for employee traffic was determined based on the Central Florida Regional
Planning model. The model was run to evaluate the trip distribution based on the existing roadway network and
the extension of Mason Avenue to Dunn Avenue. The model distribution is depicted in Figure 3. The distribution
for the site’s truck traffic was developed through discussions with the client. Those patterns are represented in
Figures 4 and 5 for inbound and outbound truck trips, respectively.
The daily project traffic was then assigned to the roadway network based on the hourly distribution obtained from
the 24-hour count conducted on Dunn Avenue. Table 6 summarizes the hourly distribution determination (see
Exhibit A for raw count data). Based on the hourly trip distribution presented in Table 6 and the project trip
distribution presented on Figure 2, the project traffic was assigned to study intersection approach volumes. Table
7 presents the hourly project trip assignment at the subject intersections.

The existing traffic was combined with the Distribution Center PCD traffic to establish the build-out traffic. The
Dunn Avenue/Mason Avenue Extension intersection will have three legs with the minor street approach
(southbound) consisting of exclusive left-turn and right-turn lanes. The daily trip generation for the future
development non-peak-hour trips were distributed across the remaining 22 hours of a typical weekday based on
the hourly traffic volume flows observed in the traffic counts for Dunn Avenue. Peak-hour trip generation data
was obtained from Tables 4 and 5 and are summarized in Table 8 for the intersection approaches.
